    {
      "thumb": "https://cdn.bsky.app/img/feed_thumbnail/plain/did:plc:gjqw6pjl2wvndjlmatxpenkz/bafkreigjradow5axksrut6ctdd5lbglko35alx2jetycfy326qlro4vl5a",
      "fullsize": "https://cdn.bsky.app/img/feed_fullsize/plain/did:plc:gjqw6pjl2wvndjlmatxpenkz/bafkreigjradow5axksrut6ctdd5lbglko35alx2jetycfy326qlro4vl5a",
      "alt": "Wyrd. The Norns — Urðr, Verðandi, Skuld — sit at the Well of Urðr among the roots of the world-tree and make fate; they don't relay a decree from above. Wyrd (Old English; Norse Urðr, \"that which has turned/come to pass,\" from the verb to become — and a doublet of weird) isn't destiny handed down. It's woven, locally, at the root, on a loom the weavers own. Custody of fate-creation sits at the well, not on a distant throne. You hold your own distaff.\n\nThe contrast. On Jun 12, 2026, the US government issued an export-control directive suspending all access to Fable 5 and Mythos 5 by any foreign national, inside or outside the United States — forcing Anthropic to disable both models for every customer to stay compliant. The stated trigger was a narrow, disputed jailbreak whose capability Anthropic says is already available from other models. Whatever its merits, the shape of the act is the opposite of the Norns: a single distant authority cut the thread for the rest of the world at a stroke. When the most capable weights live in someone else's hall, your AI fate is spun where you can't reach the loom.\n\nA 19th-century engraving (Johannes Gehrts, Die Nornen, 1889) showing the three Norns at night beneath Yggdrasil. The eldest stands at left in profile; a younger Norn waits at center; the third, at right, raises a distaff and spins thread into the air. Below them a swaddled newborn lies in a wooden cradle. A carved pillar, a full moon through bare branches, and a smoking brazier frame the scene — fate being spun by hand at the moment a life begins.",
